Just by reports or by because something's been said over and over.

45
00:04:02,825 --> 00:04:04,248
Jumping on the bandwagon.

46
00:04:04,802 --> 00:04:12,271
For instance, you know this habit that some people have, it used to be worse, where they got to be sipping water all the time.

47
00:04:13,012 --> 00:04:19,660
It seems that there were two reasons, two origins of this.

48
00:04:19,779 --> 00:04:31,653
One was concentration camps where people would approach a doctor in the concentration camp and tell them about their illness and of course all he could say was drink water.

49
00:04:32,156 --> 00:04:37,521
In drinking water, they tended at least to ameliorate the disease they had.

50
00:04:38,081 --> 00:04:49,452
But the other one was in 1945, the Food and Nutrition Board of the USA advised people to drink 2.5 liters a day, but seemingly without any research at all.

51
00:04:49,713 --> 00:04:51,233
It was just pulled out of the air.

52
00:04:52,014 --> 00:04:59,961
So it's just what you hear when you say it's this whole business of what everybody else is doing must be right.

53
00:05:01,023 --> 00:05:02,163
Same with tradition.

54
00:05:02,649 --> 00:05:06,293
It's the tradition, you know, this is the way we've always done it.

55
00:05:06,314 --> 00:05:07,636
So this is the way it's going to be.

56
00:05:08,677 --> 00:05:13,663
It tends to be very conservative, that small C, just keeping the way things are.

57
00:05:14,303 --> 00:05:18,629
And of course, it prevents creativity, of course.

58
00:05:20,771 --> 00:05:27,019
Then you get rumours, mainly anecdotal evidence, you know, just personal evidence.

59
00:05:27,178 --> 00:05:29,281
Somebody said this and therefore it must be true.

60
00:05:29,819 --> 00:05:37,471
Um, when I ran my first course up in Yorkshire, uh, near, near Thirsk, it was a beautiful, uh, big house.

61
00:05:38,312 --> 00:05:43,701
And, um, there was a man who was looking after it, Johnny and a real Yorkshire man.

62
00:05:44,201 --> 00:05:52,654
And, uh, one day we're in conversation and, uh, he was telling me that he'd smoked all his life and it had not done him any harm, you see.

63
00:05:53,295 --> 00:05:57,682
And I'd been watching him smoke and it must've just caught me the way he was doing it or something.

64
00:05:57,966 --> 00:06:01,132
So I said to him, well, do you inhale the smoke, Johnny?

65
00:06:01,452 --> 00:06:02,454
And he said, no.

66
00:06:04,177 --> 00:06:07,382
I said, well, you're obviously not going to get lung cancer.

67
00:06:08,706 --> 00:06:15,317
But of course, he would have gone around telling everybody that, you know, he smoked for 30, 40 a day and nothing's ever happened.

68
00:06:17,017 --> 00:06:24,283
There was also another story, this is way back a few years now, when there was all this stuff about paedophilia, people were afraid.

69
00:06:24,904 --> 00:06:31,911
And it seems as though somebody turned up at a house, a gang of people turned up at a house to approach this man, you know.

70
00:06:31,971 --> 00:06:37,975
And when he came out and, you know, they accused him of paedophilia, he pointed out that he wasn't.

71
00:06:38,235 --> 00:06:39,718
He was a paediatrician.

72
00:06:39,757 --> 00:06:46,062
So anyway, that's these little stories I've come across.

73
00:06:47,089 --> 00:06:50,995
Of course, religious texts, these, of course, can be quite wicked.

74
00:06:51,074 --> 00:06:54,177
We know what fundamentalists do with texts.

75
00:06:55,500 --> 00:06:58,423
But just because it's in the scriptures, it doesn't mean it's right.

76
00:06:58,463 --> 00:07:00,086
Now, that's really quite radical.

77
00:07:01,367 --> 00:07:03,930
So he's basically saying that about his own teaching.

78
00:07:07,694 --> 00:07:14,483
Also, not by inference or by logical, well, logical conjecture or by inference.

79
00:07:14,502 --> 00:07:16,404
It's very interesting that the Buddha,

80
00:07:17,531 --> 00:07:21,098
doesn't really go beyond what you can personally experience.

81
00:07:22,480 --> 00:07:26,786
He says that there's something in us which is not of this order.

82
00:07:27,086 --> 00:07:35,281
It's beyond or above or transcendent of the psychophysical organism.

83
00:07:35,821 --> 00:07:40,088
And this is the Nibbāna Dātu as it's put in Theravāna, the element of Nibbāna.

84
00:07:40,668 --> 00:07:42,391
As Mahāyāna would say,

85
00:07:42,742 --> 00:07:43,764
talk about it.

86
00:07:43,964 --> 00:07:45,026
It's our Buddha nature.

87
00:07:45,487 --> 00:07:48,971
It's this very satipanya, this intuitive awareness.

88
00:07:49,552 --> 00:07:58,745
But he never talks about what, you know, what the relationship of that is to somebody else's satipanya and what happens after death.

89
00:07:59,846 --> 00:08:03,593
Of course, there is a tradition that Buddhas are reborn in other realms.

90
00:08:04,254 --> 00:08:06,557
But the other one is that that's it.

91
00:08:06,824 --> 00:08:12,814
and something happens to that Buddha nature or that Satipañña.

92
00:08:14,257 --> 00:08:16,600
And he doesn't talk about that at all.

93
00:08:16,641 --> 00:08:32,089
In other words, there's no ultimate God, there's no Brahman, this impersonal God whom you absorb into, come out of, as it would be in, say, Hinduism.

94
00:08:32,456 --> 00:08:36,863
So there's nothing, it doesn't go beyond what can be personally experienced.

95
00:08:42,650 --> 00:08:49,220
The phrase that captures this is the map is not the territory.

96
00:08:49,740 --> 00:08:56,249
It's getting confused with ideas and logical ideas and all that with actually what's real.

97
00:08:58,392 --> 00:09:02,177
So the Buddha doesn't go into metaphysical propositions so much.

98
00:09:04,402 --> 00:09:11,789
The other one is upon axiom because it contradicts established norms or beliefs and whatnot.

99
00:09:11,809 --> 00:09:15,553
And I found that there's a special, a special title for this.

100
00:09:15,594 --> 00:09:17,956
It's called the Semmelweis Reflex.

101
00:09:18,057 --> 00:09:19,158
And this is the story.

102
00:09:19,938 --> 00:09:27,826
It derives from the name of a Hungarian physician, Ignaz Semmelweis, who discovered in 1847

103
00:09:28,177 --> 00:09:41,821
that childbed fever mortality rates fell tenfold when doctors disinfected their hands with chlorine solution before moving from one patient to another, and most particularly after an autopsy.

104
00:09:42,802 --> 00:09:51,638
At one of the two maternity wards at the University Hospital where Semmelweis worked, physicians performed autopsy on every deceased patient.

105
00:09:52,293 --> 00:10:05,089
Samovar's procedure saved many lives by stopping the ongoing contamination of patients, mostly pregnant women, with what he termed cadaverous particles.

106
00:10:05,590 --> 00:10:08,974
This is 20 years before germ theory was discovered.

107
00:10:09,754 --> 00:10:15,162
Despite overwhelming empirical evidence, his fellow doctors rejected

108
00:10:15,682 --> 00:10:24,392
I think maybe not all, but many of his fellow doctors rejected his hand washing suggestions, often for non-medical reasons.

109
00:10:24,692 --> 00:10:31,379
For instance, some doctors refused to believe that a gentleman's hand could transmit disease.

110
00:10:33,501 --> 00:10:39,028
So this is the fact and this is the way it is, and that's impossible.

111
00:10:40,229 --> 00:10:45,434
There's also specious silly reasoning, illogical reasoning.

112
00:10:46,764 --> 00:10:55,052
This is a again, it's a, it's a formal thing, they call it divine fallacy.

113
00:10:57,575 --> 00:11:11,749
If you can't understand something, if like, for instance, if you're in a, in a, in a God believing community, if you can't understand something, then then God knows, you see, everything's put down to God.

114
00:11:12,068 --> 00:11:16,332
I remember I was up in candy once where they I was up there.

115
00:11:17,038 --> 00:11:33,443
visiting and I happened to share a bench with a Muslim and we got talking and I asked him about God, you know, and he said, you know, and I said to him, you know, what's the proof that God exists, you see?

116
00:11:33,965 --> 00:11:38,010
And he just pointed to nature and said, all this, see, God made this.

117
00:11:38,511 --> 00:11:39,113
And that was it.

118
00:11:39,173 --> 00:11:39,994
That was it.

119
00:11:40,053 --> 00:11:41,375
There's no argument against that.

120
00:11:46,924 --> 00:11:51,231
By the way, this also includes conspiracy theories.

121
00:11:58,342 --> 00:12:02,489
And the final one, I think it's the final one.

122
00:12:02,850 --> 00:12:04,852
Yes, the final one.

123
00:12:04,873 --> 00:12:12,004
The final one is upon another seeming ability or

124
00:12:12,389 --> 00:12:17,374
or that this particular monk or this particular person is my teacher.

125
00:12:18,154 --> 00:12:21,278
So this is often a big mistake, isn't it?

126
00:12:21,738 --> 00:12:32,869
Where people devote themselves blindly to a teacher or to a particular tradition and they can't sort of get out of it.

127
00:12:34,530 --> 00:12:35,371
Let me see now.

128
00:12:37,293 --> 00:12:38,835
There's another bit of paper.

129
00:12:41,784 --> 00:12:50,133
Yes, given examples of this is how dare you criticize the prime minister?

130
00:12:51,855 --> 00:12:53,817
What do you know about running an entire country?

131
00:12:54,297 --> 00:12:57,179
So we won't go into that one.

132
00:12:58,181 --> 00:13:08,530
Now, usually when people mention this Kalama discourse and they point out the free thinking that the budget is saying, you know that it's up to you.

133
00:13:09,171 --> 00:13:11,033
Let me just get the quote there.

134
00:13:14,860 --> 00:13:29,321
But when, Kalama, you know for yourselves these things are wholesome, these things are blameworthy, these things are censured by the wise, these things, if accepted and undertaken, lead to harm and suffering, then you should abandon them.

135
00:13:29,341 --> 00:13:31,303
And of course, he says the opposite for what's good.

136
00:13:31,644 --> 00:13:39,916
So he's always really pushing people to investigate for themselves and to be sure for themselves by their own experience.

137
00:13:39,936 --> 00:13:44,142
So that's why it's called a charter of free thought, the Kalama Discourse.

138
00:13:44,711 --> 00:13:46,094
But he doesn't stop there.

139
00:13:46,114 --> 00:14:00,730
He does go into quite a discourse then about really the two things that he teaches throughout the scriptures, ethics and transcendence.

140
00:14:00,750 --> 00:14:03,634
This one is not so concerned with transcendence.

141
00:14:03,654 --> 00:14:11,344
It comes right at the end, as you'll see, but always about ethics.

